result.execSummary:
The defendant Wanya Timothy Johnson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Substantial Battery-Intend Bodily Harm [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Wanya Timothy Johnson in court with attorney Andrew Joel Golden.  Defendant Wanya Timothy Johnson in custody.  Daniel T Flaherty appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant. Additional statements made by: B.S. and Tyronda M.

AS TO COUNT 1: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive to count 3 and concurrent to count 4. Court STAYED the sentence(s) and placed the defendant on probation for 1 YEAR.

AS TO COUNT 3: The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 3 YEARS 6 MONTHS, consecutive to count 1 and concurrent to count 4, credit for 189 days time served. The term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 1 YEAR 6 MONTS, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS. Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 3 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 4: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction, concurrent to counts 1 and 3, with credit for 189 days served. Court STAYED the sentence(s) and placed the defendant on probation for 1 YEAR.


CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION/PROBATION:
- Serve 60 days condition time in the House of Correction as to count 3; Stayed for use by agent.
- Provide a DNA sample. 
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety.
- Complete a parenting class
- Complete domestic violence treatment.
- Third party contact only with B.S. Agent able to modify as they see fit.


- Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, and surcharges including: DNA surcharges to be paid during period of probation, if revoked to be paid by defendant's prison funds at a percentage to be determined by the DOC, remainder to be paid during the period of extended supervision; failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

*Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program OR the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
*Court denies expungement request.
